The function is to turn an array A[] of N elements into a max-heap.

```c
#define leftchild(i) (2*(i)+1)
void BuildMaxHeap(ElementType A[], int N)
{
    int i, j, child;
    ElementType Tmp;
    for (i = (N-1)/2; i >= 0; i--) {
        j = i;
        for (Tmp = A[j]; leftchild(j) < N; j = child) {
            child = leftchild(j);
            if (A[child] < A[child+1] && child != N-1) /* blank 1 */
                child++;
            if (Tmp < A[child]) /* blank 2 */
                A[j] = A[child];
            else break;
        }
        A[j] = Tmp; /* blank 3 */
    }
}
```

Blank 1: the condition to move to the right child
Blank 2: the condition to percolate down
Blank 3: place Tmp in the correct position

Level-order Traversal (20 pts)

Write a routine to list out the nodes of a binary tree in "level-order". List the root, then nodes at depth 1, followed by nodes at depth 2, and so on. You must do this in linear time.

Format of functions:
```c
void Level_order(Tree T, void (*visit)(Tree ThisNode));
```

where `void (*visit)(Tree ThisNode)` is a function that handles ThisNode being visited by Level_order, and Tree is defined as:
```c
typedef struct TreeNode *Tree;
struct TreeNode {
    ElementType Element;
    Tree Left;
    Tree Right;
};
```

Sample Output (for the tree shown in the figure):
Level-order: 3 5 6 1 8 10 9

answer.codeSnippet:
void Level_order(Tree T, void (*visit)(Tree ThisNode))
{
    if (T == NULL) return;
    Tree queue[MaxTree];
    int front = 0, rear = 0;
    queue[rear++] = T;
    while (front < rear) {
        Tree node = queue[front++];
        visit(node);
        if (node->Left) queue[rear++] = node->Left;
        if (node->Right) queue[rear++] = node->Right;
    }
}

